{
  "case_id": "D2N132",
  "method": "direct",
  "template": "soap",
  "summary_text": "S:\nThe patient reports a back injury following a fall during a surprise birthday party, where he was crunched behind others while hiding. He describes the injury as occurring when he jumped up and possibly twisted during the event. He reports pain with palpation when lying flat and with twisting motions, but denies pain or numbness radiating down his legs. He reports using ibuprofen for the pain. He also takes medication for anxiety.\n\nO:\nThe patient's examination reveals tenderness to palpation in the lumbar region with movement. Range of motion is limited by pain. Neurological examination is intact, with no reported sensory deficits or reflexes. X-ray reveals a healed lumbar fusion at L4, with no acute fractures or compression fractures. Vital signs are within normal limits.\n\nA:\nThe patient's presentation is consistent with a lumbar strain secondary to trauma. There is no evidence of nerve compression or radiculopathy.\n\nP:\nContinue ibuprofen 800 mg three times daily with food. Apply ice and heat alternating to the lumbar region. Encourage ambulation. Schedule a follow-up appointment in one week if symptoms do not improve or worsen. Order the prescribed medications and procedures.",
  "reference_summary": "CC:\n\nBack pain.\n\nHPI:\n\nMs. Lee is a 40-year-old female who presents today for an evaluation of back pain. She states she was at a birthday party and she ran her back into the railing of the staircase and twisted her back. She denies any pain radiating down her legs. Lying flat and twisting motions aggravate the pain. She is currently taking ibuprofen.\n\nCURRENT MEDICATIONS:\n\nIbuprofen.\n\nPAST MEDICAL HISTORY:\n\nAnxiety.\n\nPAST SURGICAL HISTORY:\n\nLumbar fusion\n\nEXAM\n\nExamination of the back shows range of motion without pain. Straight leg raise is negative. Sensation is intact.\n\nRESULTS\n\nX-rays of the lumbar spine show no obvious signs of acute fracture. Evidence of a prior lumbar fusion with hardware in good position.\n\nIMPRESSION\n\nLumbar spine strain.\n\nPLAN\n\nAt this point, I discussed the diagnosis and treatment options with the patient. I have recommended ice and heat. She will continue with Motrin 800 mg 3 times a day with food. She will follow up with me as needed.",
